◆ PEAK_BooleanNode_GetValue()

PEAK_C_API PEAK_BooleanNode_GetValue ( PEAK_BOOLEAN_NODE_HANDLE  booleanNodeHandle,
PEAK_NODE_CACHE_USE_POLICY  cacheUsePolicy,
PEAK_BOOL8 *  value 
)

Asks the given boolean node for its value.

Parameters
[in]booleanNodeHandleThe boolean node.
[in]cacheUsePolicyThe cache use policy.
[out]valueThe value.
Returns
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_SUCCESS Everything was fine
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_INVALID_HANDLE booleanNodeHandle is invalid
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_INVALID_ARGUMENT value is a null pointer
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_ERROR An internal error has occurred.

◆ PEAK_DataStream_KillWait()

PEAK_C_API PEAK_DataStream_KillWait ( PEAK_DATA_STREAM_HANDLE  dataStreamHandle)

Tells the given data stream to kill a wait for a finished buffer.

If there are no wait operations at the point the function gets called, the kill request gets stored. In this case the next wait operation gets killed immediately.

Parameters
[in]dataStreamHandleThe data stream.
Returns
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_SUCCESS Everything was fine
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_INVALID_HANDLE dataStreamHandle is invalid
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_ERROR An internal error has occurred.
Since

PEAK_RETURN_CODE_TIMEOUT The wait timed out
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_ERROR An internal error has occurred.
Since
1.0

◆ PEAK_EnvironmentInspector_UpdateCTIPaths()

PEAK_C_API PEAK_EnvironmentInspector_UpdateCTIPaths ( )

Collects the paths to the CTIs installed on the system.

This function depends on the architecture the library was compiled for. Therefore, this function collects 64-bit CTIs for a 64-bit library and 32-bit CTIs for a 32-bit library.

Returns
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_SUCCESS Everything was fine
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_ERROR An internal error has occurred.
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_NOT_FOUND The environment variable GENICAM_GENTL32_PATH / GENICAM_GENTL64_PATH was not found or was empty.
Since
1.0

◆ PEAK_EventController_KillWait()

PEAK_C_API PEAK_EventController_KillWait ( PEAK_EVENT_CONTROLLER_HANDLE  eventControllerHandle)

Tells the given event controller to kill a wait for an event.

If there are no wait operations at the point the function gets called, the kill request gets stored. In this case the next wait operation gets killed immediately.

Parameters
[in]eventControllerHandleThe event controller.
Returns
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_SUCCESS Everything was fine
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_INVALID_HANDLE eventControllerHandle is invalid
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_ERROR An internal error has occurred.

◆ PEAK_Library_Close()

PEAK_C_API PEAK_Library_Close ( )

Closes the IDS peak API library and cleans up any resources that are still in use.

This function should be called after no function of the library is needed anymore, before unloading the library. It cleans up any resources still in use.

Note
Calling any other function (except PEAK_Library_Initialize()) after this will return a PEAK_RETURN_CODE_NOT_INITIALIZED error.
Warning
It is of particular importance on MS Windows platforms when using "Run-Time Dynamic Linking", especially when unloading the DLL with FreeLibrary(). Otherwise it is very likely to run into the "Loader-Lock Deadlock Problem" during DLL unloading.

◆ PEAK_Library_GetLastError()

PEAK_C_API PEAK_Library_GetLastError ( PEAK_RETURN_CODE *  lastErrorCode,
char *  lastErrorDescription,
size_t *  lastErrorDescriptionSize 
)

Queries the last error.

This function is normally used by applying a two-step procedure. First of all, you call the function with all arguments except of lastErrorDescription.

// Error handling is omitted
PEAK_RETURN_CODE lastErrorCode = PEAK_RETURN_CODE_SUCCESS;
size_t size = 0;
PEAK_Library_GetLastError(&lastErrorCode, NULL, &size);

The function then gives you the last error code and the size of the error description. You could stop now if you only want to query the last error code. If you want to query the error description as well, you have to go on.

// Error handling is omitted
char errorDescription[size];
PEAK_Library_GetLastError(&returnCode, errorDescription, &size);

This two-step procedure may not be necessary if you just pass a buffer big enough for holding the description at the first function call.

Parameters
[out]lastErrorCodeThe last function error code.
[out]lastErrorDescriptionThe description for the last error.
[in,out]lastErrorDescriptionSizeIN: Size of the given buffer - OUT: Size of the returned data
Returns
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_SUCCESS Everything was fine
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_INVALID_ARGUMENT lastErrorCode and/or lastErrorCodeDescriptionSize are/is a null pointer
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_BUFFER_TOO_SMALL lastErrorDescriptionSize is too small
Since
1.0

◆ PEAK_Library_Initialize()

PEAK_C_API PEAK_Library_Initialize ( )

Initializes the IDS peak API library.

This function must be called prior to any other function call to allow global initialization of library internals. This function is necessary since automated initialization functionality like within DllMain on MS Windows platforms is very limited.

Calling this function multiple times is ok, but note that there is no reference counting, so the first call to PEAK_Library_Close() will close the library.

Note
Calling any other function before this will return a PEAK_RETURN_CODE_NOT_INITIALIZED error.

◆ PEAK_Library_IsInitialized()

◆ PEAK_NodeMap_Lock()

PEAK_C_API PEAK_NodeMap_Lock ( PEAK_NODE_MAP_HANDLE  nodeMapHandle)

Locks a recursive mutex on the NodeMap.

Use this to synchronize NodeMap access from multiple threads.

Note
Each individual access is already protected by this mutex, so the nodemap doesn't need to be locked for those. But often, nodemap access consists of multiple calls, e.g.: First, (1.) change a selector value (e.g. set "GainSelector" node to "DigitalRed"), then (2.) access a selected node (e.g. set value in "Gain" node). If a different thread changes the selector value between (1.) and (2.), (2.) will access the wrong selected node. These kinds of calls should be protected by this lock.
Parameters
[in]nodeMapHandleThe node map.
Returns
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_SUCCESS Everything was fine
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_INVALID_HANDLE nodeMapHandle is invalid
PEAK_RETURN_CODE_ERROR An internal error has occurred.
Since
1.2
